- Correctly insert the new task at the found position by adjusting the `next` pointers: `newTask.next = current.next; current.next = newTask;` <marks>1 mark</marks>

**Example Solution:**
```java
public void insertTask(Task newTask) {
    if (head == null || newTask.getPriority() > head.getPriority()) {
        newTask.next = head;
        head = newTask;
    } else {
        Task current = head;
        while (current.next != null && current.next.getPriority() >= newTask.getPriority()) {
            current = current.next;
        }
        newTask.next = current.next;
        current.next = newTask;
    }
}
```

<note>The traversal logic must ensure that the priority order is maintained (highest numeric priority first). Using `>=` in the comparison ensures that if tasks have equal priority, the new task is inserted after existing ones.</note>

<examTip>Always handle the edge case of an empty list or insertion at the head separately from middle/end insertions in linked list problems.</examTip>

