- Check if queue is full before adding ($\text{size} == \text{capacity}$) <marks>A1</marks>
- Add email message to tail and update tail pointer using modulo arithmetic ($\text{tail} = (\text{tail} + 1) \mathbin{\%} \text{capacity}$) <marks>A1</marks>
- Method signature for `dequeue` with appropriate return type <marks>A1</marks>
- Check if queue is empty before removing ($\text{size} == 0$) <marks>A1</marks>
- Remove and return email from head position and update head pointer using modulo arithmetic ($\text{head} = (\text{head} + 1) \mathbin{\%} \text{capacity}$) <marks>A1</marks>

[6 marks]

**Example implementation in Java:**

```java
public class EmailQueue {
    private Email[] queue;
    private int head = 0;
    private int tail = -1;
    private int size = 0;
    private int capacity;

    public EmailQueue(int capacity) {
        this.capacity = capacity;
        queue = new Email[capacity];
    }

    public void enqueue(Email message) {
        if (size == capacity) {
            // Queue is full
            return;
        }
        tail = (tail + 1) % capacity;
        queue[tail] = message;
        size++;
    }

    public Email dequeue() {
        if (size == 0) {
            // Queue is empty
            return null;
        }
        Email message = queue[head];
        head = (head + 1) % capacity;
        size--;
        return message;
    }
}
```

<note>Example implementation shown in Java, but other programming languages are acceptable if they demonstrate the same concepts.</note>

<examTip>Make sure to use modulo arithmetic (`%`) to handle circular array implementation.</examTip>

<commonMistake>Forgetting to update the size counter when enqueueing/dequeueing.</commonMistake>
